'''Joseph Harvey Shoctor''' (August 18, 1922 – April 19, 2001) was a Canadian theatre producer, real estate developer, and lawyer.

Shoctor was born in [[Edmonton]], Alberta in 1922, the son of a Jewish father, and grew up in the [[Boyle Street, Edmonton|Boyle Street]] neighbourhood. He first became involved in the [[theatre]] industry in his hometown, producing, writing, directing and acting with the Edmonton Little Theatre, Edmonton Light Opera, and entertaining [[World War II]] troops. After attending [[Victoria Composite High School]], he attended law school at the [[University of Alberta]] and was called to the Alberta bar in 1948. In the 1960s, he worked in [[New York City]] where he produced [[theatre]] with [[Norman Twain]].<ref>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/joseph-harvey-shoctor/ Joseph Harvey Shoctor - The Canadian Encyclopedia<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In Edmonton in 1965, he purchased the former [[Old Citadel (Edmonton)|Salvation Army Citadel]] building along with friends James L. Martin, Ralph B. MacMillan, and [[Sandy Mactaggart]]. The [[Citadel Theatre]] was founded on October 12, 1965 with its first opening night on November 10, 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citadeltheatre.com/theatre/about/ |title=History |publisher=The Citadel Theatre |accessdate=2012-03-18}}</ref> The theatre's first production to be performed was ''[[Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?]]''. Shoctor was also involved with founding of the [[Edmonton Eskimos]] of the [[Canadian Football League]], and also served as secretary-manager from 1954 to 1956. He was also governor of the [[National Theatre School of Canada]] in Montreal.<ref name="aoe">[http://www.lieutenantgovernor.ab.ca/AOE/arts/joseph-shoctor/index.html Dr. Joseph H. Shoctor | The Alberta Order of Excellence<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> A real estate developer, he worked on the planning of neighbourhoods near [[Rio Terrace, Edmonton]], and was also a proponent of revitalization of [[Downtown Edmonton]].<ref name="aoe" /><ref name="realestate" />

Shoctor was made an officer of the [[Order of Canada]] in 1986. He received the Ramon John Hnatyshyn Award for Voluntarism in the Performing Arts in 1998 and the [[Alberta Order of Excellence]] in 1990.<ref name="aoe" /> He is a member of the Edmonton Cultural Hall of Fame, inducted as a builder in 1987, and a recipient of an honorary [[doctor of laws]] from his alma mater, the University of Alberta, in 1981. A street in Edmonton, Joe Shoctor Alley, is named in his honour.<ref name="realestate">[https://wayback.archive-it.org/2217/20101208161752/http://www.albertasource.ca/realestate/people/developers_shoctor.html Alberta's Real Estate Heritage – Joe Shoctor<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

He suffered a heart attack on April 8, 2001 and died in Edmonton on April 19, 2001. His funeral was held at the [[Beth Israel Synagogue (Edmonton)|Beth Israel Synagogue]] in Edmonton and he was later buried at the Edmonton Jewish Cemetery.<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/shoctor-remembered-1.267763 Shoctor remembered - Canada - CBC News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>http://www.edmontonjewishcemetery.ca/wp-content/uploads/Shoctor-Joseph-Hyman.pdf</ref>

